Claims 6 CLAIMS 1. A device comprising: a processor; and a memory comprising instructions adapted to configure the processor to execute a method of extracting one or more Cheyne-Stokes respiration (CSR) features from respiratory polygraphy channel data comprising: a thoracic movement signal; a nasal flow rate signal; and an oxygen saturation signal, the method comprising: detecting apnea events using the nasal flow rate signal; detecting central apneas among the detected apnea events using the thoracic movement signal; detecting hypopneas using the nasal flow rate signal and the oxygen saturation signal; detecting hyperpneas from the detected central apneas, the detected hypopneas, and the nasal flow rate signal; detecting CSR cycles from the detected hyperpneas and one or more of the detected central apneas, the detected hypopneas and the nasal flow rate signal; and extracting the one or more CSR features from the detected CSR cycles. 2. A device according to claim 1, wherein the respiratory polygraphy channel data further comprises an abdominal movement signal. 3. A device according to any of claims 1 to 2, further comprising a communication interface, wherein the method further comprises transmitting the one or more CSR features to a remote computing device via the communication interface. 4. A device according to any of claims 1 to 3, further comprising a data input interface configured to receive the respiratory polygraphy channel data. 5. A respiratory polygraphy system comprising: a plurality of sensors comprising: a thoracic movement sensor configured to generate a signal representing thoracic movement of a patient; a nasal pressure transducer configured to generate a signal representing nasal flow rate of the patient; and a pulse oximeter configured to generate a signal representing oxygen saturation of the patient; a memory configured to store channel data representing the thoracic movement signal, the nasal flow rate signal, and the oxygen saturation signal; and a processor configured to execute a method of extracting one or more Cheyne- Stokes respiration (CSR) features from the stored channel data, the method comprising: detecting apnea events using the nasal flow rate signal; detecting central apneas among the detected apnea events using the thoracic movement signal; detecting hypopneas using the nasal flow rate signal and the oxygen saturation signal; detecting hyperpneas from the detected central apneas, the detected hypopneas, and the nasal flow rate signal; 

 detecting CSR cycles from the detected hyperpneas, the detected central apneas, and the detected hypopneas; and extracting the one or more CSR features from the detected CSR cycles. 6. A system according to claim 5, wherein the plurality of sensors further comprises an abdominal movement sensor configured to generate a signal representing abdominal movement of a patient. 7. A system according to any of claims 5 to 6, wherein the processor is co-located with the memory. 8. A system according to claim 7, further comprising a communication interface, wherein the method further comprises transmitting the one or more CSR features to a remote computing device via the communication interface. 9. A system according to any of claims 5 to 6, wherein the processor forms part of a computing device that is remote from the memory. 10. A system according to claim 9, further comprising a communication interface, wherein the method further comprises receiving the signals from the sensors via the communication interface. 11. A method of extracting one or more Cheyne-Stokes respiration (CSR) features from respiratory polygraphy channel data of a patient, the method comprising: detecting apnea events using a nasal flow rate signal of the respiratory polygraphy channel data; detecting central apneas among the detected apnea events using a thoracic movement signal of the respiratory polygraphy channel data; detecting hypopneas using the nasal flow rate signal and an oxygen saturation signal of the respiratory polygraphy channel data; detecting hyperpneas from the detected central apneas, the detected hypopneas, and the nasal flow rate signal; 

 detecting CSR cycles from the detected hyperpneas and one or more of the detected central apneas, the detected hypopneas and the nasal flow rate signals; and extracting the one or more CSR features from the detected CSR cycles. 12. A method according to claim 11, further comprising detecting desaturation events using the oxygen saturation signal of the respiratory polygraphy channel data. 13. A method according to claim 12, wherein detecting hypopneas uses the detected desaturation events. 14. A method according to claim 13, wherein detecting hypopneas comprises: detecting hypopneas using the nasal flow rate signal; and discarding a detected hypopnea that is not followed by a desaturation event. 15. A method according to any of claims 11 to 14, further comprising discarding a detected hypopnea that overlaps with a detected apnea event. 16. A method according to any of claims 12 to 14, wherein the one or more CSR features comprise lung-to-periphery circulation time, and the extracting one or more CSR features uses the detected desaturation events. 17. A method according to any of claims 11 to 14, wherein the detecting CSR cycles comprises: determining whether a duration of a hyperpnea is within a predetermined range; and labelling, based on the determining, a sequence of a central apnea or hypopnea followed by a hyperpnea as a CSR cycle. 18. A method according to claim 17, further comprising discarding CSR cycles not forming part of a sequence of at least two consecutive CSR cycles. 19. A method according to claim 17, further comprising determining whether a correlation of an envelope of the nasal flow rate signal during a hyperpnea with a CSR template exceeds a predetermined threshold. 20. A method according to claim 19, wherein the envelope is an upper envelope. 21. A method according to any of claims 11 to 19, wherein detecting central apneas comprises determining whether an amplitude of the thoracic movement signal during an apnea event drops by an amount that exceeds a thoracic movement threshold for longer than a predetermined duration. 22. A method according to claim 21, wherein the thoracic movement threshold is a fraction of a mean amplitude of the thoracic movement signal over a window preceding the start of the apnea event. 23. A method according to any of claims 21 to 22, wherein the respiratory polygraphy channel data further comprises an abdominal movement signal. 24. A method according to claim 23, wherein detecting central apneas further comprises determining whether an amplitude of the abdominal movement signal during an apnea event drops by an amount that exceeds an abdominal movement threshold for longer than a predetermined duration. 25. A method according to claim 24, wherein the abdominal movement threshold is a fraction of a mean amplitude of the abdominal movement signal over a window preceding the start of the apnea event. 26. A method according to any of claims 21 to 25, wherein detecting central apneas further comprises determining whether a total duration of valid breaths during the apnea event is less than a predetermined fraction of the duration of the apnea event. 27. A method according to claim 26, wherein a valid breath is a breath whose total time falls within a valid range. 28. A method according to claim 27, wherein the valid range is bounded by the reciprocals of an estimated respiratory rate plus or minus a tolerance. 29. A method according to any of claims 11 to 28, further comprising discarding windows containing gross bodily movement from the thoracic movement signal before detecting the central apneas. 30. A method according to claim 29, wherein the discarding comprises: 

 normalising the thoracic movement signal; and discarding a window of the thoracic movement signal in which a variance of the normalised thoracic movement signal exceeds a threshold. 31. A method according to any of claims 11 to 30, further comprising pre-filtering the nasal flow rate signal to obtain a respiratory component of the nasal flow rate signal. 32. A method according to any of claims 11 to 31, further comprising pre-filtering the thoracic movement signal by a band-pass filter to remove low-frequency noise, baseline wander, cardiac noise, and high frequency movement. 33. A method according to any of claims 11 to 32, wherein detecting hyperpneas comprises determining whether an upper envelope of the nasal flow rate signal between two adjacent events exceeds a predetermined constant times a recent mean ventilation for longer than a predetermined duration. 34. A method according to claim 33, further comprising estimating the recent mean ventilation by applying a low-pass filter to the nasal flow rate signal. 35. A method according to any of claims 33 to 34, wherein the events are central apneas or hypopneas. 36. A method according to any of claims 33 to 35, wherein the respiratory polygraphy channel data further comprises an abdominal movement signal. 37. A method according to claim 36, wherein the events are central apneas or central hypopneas. 38. A method according to claim 37, further comprising detecting central hypopneas among the detected hypopneas using the thoracic movement signal and the abdominal movement signal. 39. A method according to claim 38, wherein detecting central hypopneas comprises: detecting periods of paradoxical breathing in the thoracic movement signal and the abdominal movement signal, and 

 labelling hypopneas that coincide with periods of paradoxical breathing as obstructive. 40. A method according to any of claims 38 to 39, further comprising discarding windows containing gross bodily movement from the abdominal movement signal before detecting the central hypopneas. 41. A method according to any of claims 36 to 40, further comprising pre-filtering the abdominal movement signal by a band-pass filter to remove low-frequency noise, baseline wander, cardiac noise, and high frequency movement. 42. A method according to any of claims 11 to 41, wherein the one or more CSR features comprise one or more of: apnea length; ventilation length; cycle length; time to peak flow; lung-to-periphery circulation time; and loop gain. 43. A method according to any of claims 11 to 42, further comprising pre-filtering the oxygen saturation signal to remove artefacts resulting from gross bodily movement of the patient. 44. A respiratory polygraphy system comprising: means for generating a signal representing thoracic movement of a patient; means for generating a signal representing nasal flow rate of the patient; and means for generating a signal representing oxygen saturation of the patient; means for detecting apnea events using the nasal flow rate signal; 

 means for detecting central apneas among the detected apnea events using the thoracic movement signal; means for detecting hypopneas using the nasal flow rate signal and the oxygen saturation signal; means for detecting hyperpneas from the detected central apneas, the detected hypopneas, and the nasal flow rate signal; means for detecting CSR cycles from the detected hyperpneas, the detected central apneas, and the detected hypopneas; and means for extracting one or more CSR features from the detected CSR cycles. 45. A device comprising: a processor; and a memory comprising instructions adapted to configure the processor to execute a method of extracting one or more Cheyne-Stokes respiration (CSR) features from respiratory polygraphy channel data comprising: a thoracic movement signal; an abdominal movement signal; a nasal flow rate signal; and an oxygen saturation signal. 46. A device according to claim 45, further comprising a communication interface, wherein the method further comprises transmitting the one or more CSR features to a remote computing device via the communication interface. 47. A device according to any of claims 45 to 46, further comprising a data input interface configured to receive the respiratory polygraphy channel data. 48. A respiratory polygraphy system comprising: a plurality of sensors comprising: 

 a thoracic movement sensor configured to generate a signal representing thoracic movement of a patient; an abdominal movement sensor configured to generate a signal representing abdominal movement of a patient; a nasal pressure transducer configured to generate a signal representing nasal flow rate of the patient; and a pulse oximeter configured to generate a signal representing oxygen saturation of the patient; a memory configured to store the thoracic movement signal, the nasal flow rate signal, and the oxygen saturation signal; and a processor configured to execute a method of extracting one or more Cheyne- Stokes respiration (CSR) features from the stored signals. 49. A system according to claim 48, wherein the processor is co-located with the memory. 50. A system according to claim 49, further comprising a communication interface, wherein the method further comprises transmitting the one or more CSR features to a remote computing device via the communication interface. 51. A system according to claim 48, wherein the processor forms part of a computing device that is remote from the memory. 52. A system according to claim 51, further comprising a communication interface, wherein the method further comprises receiving the signals from the sensors via the communication interface. 53. A method of extracting one or more Cheyne-Stokes respiration (CSR) features from respiratory polygraphy channel data of a patient, the method comprising: detecting apnea events using a nasal flow rate signal of the respiratory polygraphy channel data; 

 detecting central apneas among the detected apnea events using a thoracic movement signal and an abdominal movement signal of the respiratory polygraphy channel data; detecting hypopneas using the nasal flow rate signal and an oxygen saturation signal of the respiratory polygraphy channel data; detecting central hypopneas among the detected hypopneas using the thoracic movement signal and the abdominal movement signal; detecting hyperpneas from the detected central apneas, the detected central hypopneas, and the nasal flow rate signal; detecting CSR cycles from the detected hyperpneas and one or more of the detected central apneas, and the detected central hypopneas; and extracting the one or more CSR features from the detected CSR cycles. 54. A method according to claim 53, wherein detecting central apneas comprises: determining whether an amplitude of the thoracic movement signal during an apnea event drops by an amount that exceeds a thoracic movement threshold for longer than a predetermined duration, and determining whether an amplitude of the abdominal movement signal during an apnea event drops by an amount that exceeds an abdominal movement threshold for longer than a predetermined duration. 55. A method according to any of claims 53 to 54, further comprising discarding windows containing gross bodily movement from the abdominal movement signal before detecting the central apneas. 56. A method according to any of claims 53 to 55, wherein detecting central hypopneas comprises: detecting periods of paradoxical breathing in the thoracic movement signal and the abdominal movement signal, and 

 labelling hypopneas that coincide with periods of paradoxical breathing as obstructive. 57. A method according to claim 56, further comprising discarding windows containing gross bodily movement from the abdominal movement signal before detecting the central hypopneas. 58. A method according to any of claims 53 to 57, further comprising pre-filtering the abdominal movement signal by a band-pass filter to remove low-frequency noise, baseline wander, cardiac noise, and high frequency movement. 59. A respiratory polygraphy system comprising: means for generating a signal representing thoracic movement of a patient; means for generating a signal representing abdominal movement of a patient; means for generating a signal representing nasal flow rate of the patient; means for generating a signal representing oxygen saturation of the patient; and means for extracting one or more Cheyne-Stokes respiration (CSR) features from the signals.
